Ptolemaic Kingship in the Legend of the Origins of the Septuagint -- t16. The Production of Greek Books in Alexandrian Judaism -- t17. The Septuagint: Translating and Adapting the Torah to the 3rd Century BCE -- t18. Greek Historians on Jews and Judaism in the 3rd Century BCE -- tV. Biblical Texts in the 3rd Century BCE -- t19. How to Identify a Ptolemaic Period Text in the Hebrew Bible -- t20. No Prophetic Texts from the Hellenistic Period? -- t21. The Social Setting and Purpose of Early Judean Apocalyptic Literature -- t22. “To be destroyed, to be killed, and to be annihilated” (Esther 7:4) -- tIndex of Ancient Sources -- tIndex of Geographical Names -- tIndex of Subjects -- tIndex of Modern Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis multidisciplinary study takes a fresh look at Judean history and biblical literature in the late fourth and third centuries BCE. In a major reappraisal of this era, the contributions to this volume depict it as one in which critical changes took place.Until recently, the period from Alexander’s conquest in 332 BCE to the early years of Seleucid domination following Antiochus III’s conquest in 198 BCE was reputed to be poorly documented in material evidence and textual production, buttressing the view that the era from late Persian to Hasmonean times was one of seamless continuity. Biblical scholars believed that no literary activity belonged to the Hellenistic age, and archaeologists were unable to refine their understanding because of a lack of secure chronological markers. However, recent studies are revealing this period as one of major social changes and intense literary activity. Historians have shed new light on the nature of the Hellenistic empires and the relationship between the central power and local entities in ancient imperial settings, and the redating of several biblical texts to the third century BCE challenges the traditional periodization of Judean history.Bringing together Hellenistic history, the archaeology of Judea, and biblical studies, this volume appraises the early Hellenistic period anew as a time of great transition and change and situates Judea within its broader regional and transregional imperial contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aBerlin, Andrea M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChrubasik, Boris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarhi, Yoav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGadot, Yuval, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGambash, Gil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarfinkel, Yosef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzalez, Hervé, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGorre, Gilles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrabbe, Lester L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerbert, Sharon C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonigman, Sylvie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonigman, Sylvie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKratz, Reinhard G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreimerman, Igor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLim, Timothy H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipschits, Oded, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipschits, Oded, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLorber, Catharine C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l